# PostgreSQL

Start a MySQL server.

Launch Terminator.

Type d run --name LiferayBD -e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=madeofdust -p 3309:3309 -d postgres

This runs a Docker image called LiferayBD in the background.

Type d logs LiferayBD to see its startup logs.

Type telnet localhost 3307.

Trying ::1...
telnet: connect to address ::1: Connection refused
Trying 127.0.0.1...
telnet: connect to address 127.0.0.1: Connection refused
This command fails because nothing is running on port 3307.

Type telnet localhost 3309.

Trying ::1...
Connected to localhost.
Escape character is '^]'.
J
8.0.22	Wxb;bOï¿½C(=k~|Mcaching_sha2_password
This command works because LiferayBD is running on port 3309.

Type <CONTROL+]> and then type quit to exit out of telnet on port 3309.

Type d stop LiferayBD.

Type telnet localhost 3309. This command fails because postgres is stopped.

Type d rm LiferayBD.

Type d start LiferayBD. This command fails because we deleted the Docker container called LiferayBD.

Type d run --name LiferayBD -d -e LiferayBD_ROOT_PASSWORD=lovethepoor -p 3309:3309 postgres:8.0.22 to recreate the Docker container.

Type d exec -it LiferayBD mysql -uroot -p to run the postgres client that exists on the postgres server. Your password is lovethepoor.

The command can be split into two parts. The first part, d exec -it LiferayBD, tells Docker to execute a command on the LiferayBD container. The second part, mysql -uroot -p, is the command that is run on the container itself.
Type show databases;. This lists the databases available in MySQL.

+--------------------+
| Database           |
+--------------------+
| information_schema |
| mysql              |
| performance_schema |
| sys                |
+--------------------+
Type use mysql;.

Type show tables;. This lists the tables in the mysql database. Note that the MySQL server happens to have a database within it called mysql. This is the mysql database and not the the mysql client referenced in d exec -it galatians mysql -uroot -p.

Type use information_schema;.

Type show tables;.

Type quit to exit the container.

Type d stop galatians and d start galatians to restart the container. This step is not necessary but is written here so you know how to restart a container based on its name.

Connect to a MySQL server with a MySQL client over the network.

Get your IP.

Type d run --rm -it mysql:8.0.22 mysql -h192.168.xxx.xxx -uroot -p. Replace 192.168.xxx.xxx with your IP.

Type quit to exit the container.

1. Start a server with PostgreSQL
  i. Launch terminal
  ii. d exec -it LiferayBD sh
  iii. /usr/bin/psql -U postgres postgres
  
  
